[5] Immunity after vaccination
Date: Thu 26 May 2022 11:04 PM
Source: Yahoo Life [abridged, edited]
https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/dr-fauci-just-gave-concerning-210412961.html


Monkeypox is a disease that is caused by infection with the monkeypox virus, according to the CDC. The virus belongs to the _Orthopoxvirus_ genus, with also includes the virus that causes smallpox. As a result, some people might already be protected from monkeypox disease thanks to previous smallpox vaccinations. According to The New York Times, routine immunization for smallpox stopped in 1972 for most people in the US, although the military continued to be vaccinated against the virus until 1991.

"Because monkeypox virus is closely related to the virus that causes smallpox, the smallpox vaccine can protect people from getting monkeypox," the CDC explains.

But Dr Fauci has just given a concerning warning about people's protection. Even if you've had a previous smallpox vaccine, that may not be protecting you from monkeypox. Anthony Fauci, MD, the White House's top COVID adviser, told The New York Times on [26 May 2022] that people began questioning the smallpox vaccine's durability in 2001, following an anthrax attack. According to Fauci, it is reasonable to assume most vaccinated people are still protected, "but durability of protection varies from person to person. "We can't guarantee that a person who was vaccinated against smallpox is still going to be protected against monkeypox," Fauci told The New York Times.

According to the CDC, smallpox vaccines are believed to be effective at protecting people against monkeypox when given before exposure to virus, but also after exposure to potentially help prevent the disease or make it less severe. "Persons exposed to monkeypox virus and who have not received the smallpox vaccine within the last 3 years, should consider getting vaccinated," the CDC says on its website. "The sooner the person receives the vaccine, the more effective it will be in protecting against monkeypox virus."

Currently, the agency recommends boosters of smallpox vaccines every few years, but only "for persons at risk of occupation exposure," David Daigle, a spokesman for the CDC, said in a statement to The New York Times.

"Until we know more, we will be using available vaccine stocks for people who've had close contact with known cases, and people at highest risk for exposure through their jobs, like health care workers treating monkeypox patients," Daigle said.

[Byline: Kali Coleman]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[In the New York Times report cited above (https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/26/health/monkeypox-vaccine-immunity.html)," Dr Ferrucci and his colleagues at the NIH [National Institutes of Health], as well as other teams, have also found that antibody levels persist for decades after vaccination. Some studies have found that other branches of the immune system also wane slowly, but antibodies produced from smallpox vaccination may be enough on their own to protect against monkeypox."

"Laboratory evidence of antibodies does not prove that smallpox vaccination can protect against monkeypox. But answering that question would require that study participants be deliberately infected with smallpox or a related virus, an obviously unethical experiment."

"In 2003, dozens of Americans became infected with monkeypox after being exposed to infected prairie dogs. Of the 8 people who had previously been vaccinated, 5 developed an average of 3 pus-filled blisters, compared with an average of 33 in those who were unvaccinated. The other 3 vaccinated individuals had no symptoms at all. "They didn't even know they had been infected."

"Another study of that outbreak found that in a family of 3, the previously vaccinated father developed just 2 monkeypox lesions compared with 200 in the unvaccinated mother. Their unvaccinated 6-year-old daughter had about 90 lesions and was in a coma for 12 days (https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/190/10/1833/2191730?login=false)."

It will be interesting to learn as this outbreak continues if cases do not occur in individuals 50 years of age and older who have received smallpox vaccinations in the past. - Mod.TY]

