[7] Virus mutations and transmission
Date: Thu 26 May 2022 10:12 AM BST
Source: i News [edited]
https://inews.co.uk/news/health/monkeypox-virus-could-have-mutated-to-become-more-transmissible-between-humans-1651452


Scientists investigating the monkeypox outbreak are keeping an open mind about whether the virus has mutated to transmit more easily among humans, it has emerged.

The possibility that the cluster of cases in the UK, Europe and other regions where it is not endemic was triggered by "superspreader" events in Belgium and the Canary Islands is still a strong line of enquiry.

But sequencing of the monkeypox virus genome from this 2022 outbreak has shown some mutations have occurred which could be associated with human-to-human transmission.

Experts emphasised that it is too early to say whether the mutations have made the virus more transmissible, but it is being investigated as a possible factor.

The virus associated with this outbreak is not being classed as a new variant but rather a sublineage of the existing variant [clade] that is endemic in West Africa.

Scientists at the Genomics and Bioinformatics Unit of the National Institute of Health Doutor Ricardo Jorge in Lisbon, Portugal identified mutations in genomic sequences from 9 patients infected in the current monkeypox outbreak.

In a discussion on the forum virological.org [https://virological.org/], they detail "the 1st signs of microevolution within the outbreak cluster" including 7 genetic mutations.

There are also signs of gene deletion in the genomes from this outbreak, which could potentially point to increased transmission, the Portuguese researchers said.

Aris Katzourakis, professor of evolution and genomics at Oxford University's department of zoology, told "i" it was too early to say whether the changes were leading to increased transmission. He said there were signs in the 2022 genomes of "hypermutation" caused by the host's antiviral defences. He added: "It seems that it is possible that in this case, this set of mutations has enabled an 'evolutionary leap' in these monkeypox sequences, causing them to diverge more than would be expected.

"We don't know the functional consequences of this, but this certainly merits investigation in the light of potential for adaptation to human-to-human transmission.

"It is known that large DNA viruses like the poxviruses can evolve relatively rapidly by gene deletion, compared to the relative to the quite slow process of sequence change. "It's not unreasonable to imagine that this deletion could be involved in human-to-human transmission, however not all of the monkeypox genomes sequenced to date appear to bear it.

"The bottom line is there are several lines of enquiry for exploring whether these monkeypox genomes might be better adapted to human-to-human transmission. "However, it is too early to say whether this is a certainty, and to weigh this up against the potential transmission advantage of entering a well-connected transmission group."

Tom Wenseleers, a professor of evolutionary biology at the University of Leuven, Belgium, tweeted: "It remains an open question whether this new lineage could have different transmissibility. "If it would, it could provide a parsimonious answer to the question, 'Why do we see this international outbreak now?', but several factors likely contribute."

[Byline: Jane Merrick]

